WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
6.0 English From BBC LearningEnglish.com

2
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBC LearningEnglish. I'm Beth and I'm Pippa.

3
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Everywhere you look online from gaming and fashion to music, travel and culture, you'll find social media influences.

4
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
These social media influences do what their famous for, influencing and creating trends.

5
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Do you follow any social media influences, Beth?

6
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I don't follow any specifically, I would say, but I do see influences on Facebook and Instagram.

7
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Well, the most successful influences have millions of followers.

8
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:53.000
And not surprisingly, this has caught the attention of another group of people trying to get their message out to the public.

9
00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Politicians using the media to win elections is nothing new, but in this episode we'll be finding out what happens when social media influences become politicians themselves.

10
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:15.000
As usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases, and remember there's a transcript of this episode to read along with why you listen.

11
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:20.000
It's available now on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com

12
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:29.000
But first, I have a question for you, Beth. The most followed Instagram account of 2025 belongs to Football, Cristiano Ronaldo.

13
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
But how many followers does he have?

14
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:40.000
A6.7 million, B67 million, or C667 million.

15
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Oh, I'm going to go down the middle, 67 million.

16
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
Well, we'll find out the answer later in the program.

17
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:53.000
And the world's politicians are realising that they can reach a lot of people through social media influences.

18
00:01:53.000 --> 00:02:02.000
There have even been allegations of politicians paying for the support of influences in places like Columbia, Argentina, and Indonesia.

19
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
And one place where politics has become a big topic on social media is Nigeria.

20
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Nigeria is a country with a huge young population.

21
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.000
There are around 200 million people in total, and 70% of them are under 30.

22
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Many of these young voters are turned off, meaning not interested in traditional media.

23
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
But they do follow social media influences.

24
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Aglino Carey is BBCEbo News Editor in Lagos Nigeria.

25
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.000
She spoke with BBC World Service Program the fifth floor about the situation there.

26
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Iflensers are super important to shaping the narrative of these young people, some of them started, you know,

27
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:54.000
activism, some of them started out with lifestyle and then branched into politics.

28
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Adeline thinks influences are super important in Nigerian politics.

29
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.000
She uses super to mean very extremely on more than usual.

30
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
For example, if you say you're super happy about something, you mean you're very happy about it.

31
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
In Nigeria, influencers are shaping the narrative of elections.

32
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
If someone shapes the narrative, they have a strong influence over how something is presented or understood.

33
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:31.000
Influencing things, of course, is exactly what influences do, but now more and more social media personalities are branching out into politics.

34
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:38.000
When you branch out, you start doing something different from what you usually do, such as a new activity or job.

35
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.000
So what happens when influences become politicians themselves?

36
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Here Adeline Carey explains more to Farinakamidi, presenter of BBC World Services, the fifth floor.

37
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:57.000
What about a Nigerian? Is there a pushback against these influencers who got involved in promoting political parties?

38
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Absolutely. You just push back.

39
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:08.000
They also go back and dig up information about these people from their personal lives and then publish them on social media.

40
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:14.000
In Nigeria, there was a pushback against social media influencers turned politicians.

41
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.000
A pushback is a negative reaction or rejection of something that has happened.

42
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:27.000
In fact, the public reaction was so bad people started to dig up information about influences who promote politicians.

43
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
If you dig up information about someone, you try to find details about them.

44
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:40.000
We have a similar phrase, dig up dirt on someone, which means trying to find information about someone which could damage their reputation.

45
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So social media can be a powerful tool for politicians.

46
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.000
But getting involved in politics doesn't always go well for social media influencers.

47
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Okay, Pippur, isn't it time you revealed the answer to your question?

48
00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Yes, I asked how many followers does Cristiano Ronaldo, the footballer, have, and the answer was C667 million at the time of recording.

49
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.000
That's a lot more than I have, Beth.

50
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And me, wow.

51
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with the phrasal verb, turned off, meaning uninterested.

52
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:23.000
When super is placed before an adjective, it means very or more than usual.

53
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Social media influencers who shape the narrative have a strong influence over how something is presented or understood.

54
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:37.000
If you branch out into something new, you start doing an activity or job that is different from what you usually do.

55
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
A pushback is a negative reaction to something new that has happened.

56
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:47.000
And finally, the phrasal verb dig up means to try and find information.

57
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:54.000
This is often about a person and their private life in order to try and damage their reputation.

58
00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but why not head over to our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com to try the quiz and work sheets for this episode.

59
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
See you there soon, but for now, goodbye.

60
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.000
Bye.

61
